ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_code.c:455-462` (`exp2reg`) materializes deferred boolean/not expressions into `e->v.idx` after calling `var2reg()`. For locals (`ETLOCAL`), `var2reg()` simply returns the original local register and does not honor the requested destination register. Thus compiling `var j = !i` emits boolean materialization (`JMPF/LDBOOL`) into `R0` (the parameter `i`) and only then moves it to `R1` (`j`). The debug dump confirmed buggy bytecode for `f(i): var j = !i; return i` as `JMPF R0 ...; LDBOOL R0 ...; MOVE R1 R0; RET R0`, so `i` is overwritten with `false`.

LOCAL FIX: In `exp2reg()`, before emitting the conditional materialization jump/load sequence, ensure a non-`ETREG` source is copied into the requested destination register and update the expression descriptor to that register. The tested minimal patch was to insert before `appendjump(...)`:
```c
if (e->type != ETREG) {
    code_move(finfo, dst, reg);
    if (dst == finfo->freereg) {
        be_code_allocregs(finfo, 1);
    }
    e->type = ETREG;
    e->v.idx = dst;
}
```
and then emit `jpt = appendjump(...)`. This changes the bytecode to `MOVE R1 R0; JMPF R1 ...; LDBOOL R1 ...; RET R0`, preserving `i`.

GLOBAL FIX: Redesign/enforce the compiler codegen contract so functions that accept a destination register either always honor it or explicitly report that they returned an immutable/source register. In particular, split “read location” (`ETLOCAL`, `ETCONST`, globals) from “writable temporary result” (`ETREG`) in the expression descriptor API, add assertions in `exp2reg()` that conditional materialization never writes to a local/const source unless it was first copied, and add bytecode-level regression tests for unary/boolean materialization in assignments, returns, call arguments, and ternary expressions to catch source-register clobbering.

